{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"952d90cb-78c7-4fe4-a6b4-969e74020f1e","content":"## Using MCP Inspector with a C# stdio Server\n\nRun the inspector via `npx`:\n\n```bash\nnpx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector dotnet run --project /path/to/your/McpServer.csproj\n```\n\nThis launches a web UI (usually at `http://localhost:5173`) that connects to your server over stdio.\n\n**In the Inspector UI you can:**\n- **List Tools** – see all tools your server exposes\n- **Call Tools** – fill in parameters and invoke them interactively\n- **View JSON-RPC traffic** – inspect raw request/response messages\n- **Test prompts & resources** – if your server exposes those\n\n**Tips:**\n- If your server needs arguments, append them: `npx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector dotnet run --project ./src/MyServer -- --my-flag`\n- Pass environment variables with `-e`: `npx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector -e API_KEY=xxx dotnet run`\n- Add `--server-url http://localhost:PORT` if you need to change the inspector's server port\n- For debugging in your C# code, attach a debugger to the `dotnet` process the inspector spawns, or add `Debugger.Launch()` in your startup path","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6e17a94b-7efa-4e41-b84c-76838d44aabe","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to use the MCP Inspector to interactively test and debug a C# MCP server that uses stdio transport. This is a general knowledge question about tooling — I don't need to explore a codebase for this. I can answer directly.\n\nLet me provide a concise, practical answer about using the MCP Inspector with a stdio-based C# MCP server.","outputTokens":396,"requestId":"158A:301230:315D81B:360C8E6:69FBE597"},"id":"41930cc0-2679-4c12-9e79-fa5f36198171","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:06:41.724Z","parentId":"1154067b-0aa8-4875-90ca-095c406345ae"}
